## IX.1 Time Is Not a Dimension

The standard treatment of special and general relativity represents
time as the fourth dimension of spacetime. This is mathematically
convenient and empirically successful. It may also be a fiction.

**The argument:**

Every clock is an oscillator. A pendulum swings back and forth.
An atomic clock counts electron transitions at 9.192 GHz. The Earth
rotates. All timekeeping is counting oscillations and mapping that
count onto a real number line called *t*. The map is useful. The map
is not the territory.

The photon makes the fiction visible. Standard SR says the photon
moves through the time dimension at infinite speed (γ → ∞). No
physical clock measures infinite time-coordinate distance. The photon
has no rest mass, no internal states, no Zitterbewegung oscillator.
It does not experience time because time — as a local count of
oscillations along an entropy gradient — requires an oscillator and
internal states. The photon has neither.

**What time actually is in the Cameron framework:**

```
TIME IS:
  Local:    each massive particle has its own clock
            — the Zitterbewegung oscillation at f = mc²/h
  Directed: by the entropy gradient established at the Big Bounce
            — the second law IS time's arrow, not its consequence
  Bounded:  by the null geodesic (c is the causal limit, not a speed)
  Relative: because oscillator rates depend on velocity through γ

TIME IS NOT:
  A dimension through which we move
  Universal (no absolute simultaneity)
  Experienced by photons (no oscillator, no clock)
  Separable from matter (no matter = no clock = no time)
```

The imaginary PMV P_im = mc is the particle's intrinsic oscillator.
It oscillates at the de Broglie frequency f = mc²/h — the
Zitterbewegung. Time dilation is real because the oscillator rate
depends on velocity through γ. Different velocities give different
oscillator rates. No fourth dimension is required.

**What needs to be derived:**

A formal demonstration that the Lorentz transformation follows from
the γ-dependence of the Zitterbewegung rate alone, without invoking
time as a dimension.

