## IX.3 Antimatter as Opposite Phase Rotation Direction

Dirac's equation has four solutions. Feynman's reinterpretation
identified the negative energy solutions as antiparticles moving
backward in time. In the Cameron framework where time is not a
dimension, this requires restatement.

```
Particle:     Zitterbewegung ∝ e^(+imc²t/ℏ)  — counterclockwise
Antiparticle: Zitterbewegung ∝ e^(-imc²t/ℏ)  — clockwise
```

Both rotate at the same rate |mc²/ℏ|. Both have positive energy mc².
Both move forward in the entropy gradient — confirmed by ALPHA-g
(2023). The imaginary charge (gravitational mass) has the same sign
for both.

**The highway analogy:** Two cars on a highway, both moving north.
Both have their wheels turning forward. Both PMVs point in the same
imaginary direction. But Car A turns its steering wheel to orbit
counterclockwise. Car B turns clockwise. Relative to Car A, Car B's
circular motion appears to run backward — even though both are moving
forward in the entropy gradient. This is what Feynman called "backward
in time." It is not backward in time. It is a mirror image path
through phase space.

**Why annihilation is phase cancellation:**

```
e^(+imc²t/ℏ) × e^(-imc²t/ℏ) = e^0 = 1
```

The two oscillators cancel. No oscillator → no local time → no matter.
The energy 2mc² propagates as photons. Information is preserved in the
photon pair's relative phase, polarization, and momentum.

**What needs to be derived:**

A formal demonstration that the four Dirac solutions correspond
precisely to the four combinations of phase rotation direction (±ω)
and spin orientation (↑↓) in the Cameron PMV framework, with correct
transformation properties under CPT.

