## IX.8 The Language of Early Universe Emissions

*This section preserves a terminological lesson that emerged from
developing the framework. The wrong word carries false physical
implications. The right word encodes the physics precisely.*

**Why "laser" is wrong for any of these events:**

A laser requires population inversion, stimulated emission, and
optical feedback. None of the early universe emission events have all
three. The CMB is the most nearly perfect blackbody spectrum ever
measured — maximum entropy, thermally incoherent. Calling it a
"cosmic laser" implies coherence and low entropy. It has neither.

**The correct framework:**

Each emission event in the early universe is the radiation signature
of a phase transition. The Cameron framework gives each one a specific
character along two axes: sector (real/imaginary/mixed) and entropy
character (reset/maximum/reduction/frozen/increasing/reorganised).

| Event | Sector | Entropy | Correct term |
|---|---|---|---|
| Bounce annihilation | Real | Reset | Topological phase transition emission |
| Thermal equilibrium | Real | Maximum | Blackbody radiation |
| Nuclear binding γ-rays | Mixed | Reduction | Nuclear condensation radiation |
| CMB — recombination | Real | Reorganised | Thermal decoupling radiation |
| Neutrino decoupling | Imaginary | Frozen | Imaginary sector information snapshot |
| Neutron decay ν̄ | Imaginary | Increasing | Sector crossing emission |

**The terminological principle:**

*Use "phase transition emission" with sector and entropy character
specified. Never use "laser," "coherent emission," or "stimulated
emission" for any of these events unless population inversion,
stimulated emission, and optical feedback are explicitly demonstrated.*

*The CMB is thermal decoupling radiation — maximum entropy, thermally
incoherent. The neutrino decoupling is an imaginary sector information
snapshot. Nuclear binding releases nuclear condensation radiation.*

This principle applies to all sections of this framework and to all
public-facing narrative documents.

